This project is designed to improve the absorptive, adaptive and transformative resilience capacities for 15,505 households (62,021 individuals) in Mutoko and Mudzi districts, both extremely vulnerable to drought and exhibiting high poverty levels. Communities that lack resilience to shocks and stresses represent leaky systems - systems where human, social, environmental and economic capital is lost or wasted. This project has been designed to plug the leaks in these systems, harnessing local and external resources to strengthen their functionality, productivity, and health. The project will work in a consortium of five agencies namely BIZ, CADS, SH, NCT & CA, all with long term presence and experience in the target districts.

This project will address the escalated health risks due to COVID-19 pandemic and preparedness of most vulnerable and critically affected ethnic minorities and Internally displaced population (IDPs) living in most fragile and hard-to-reach areas, with current spike of COVID-19 cases compounded by already poor health governance and health access systems in Myanmar.

About the USAID Reducing conflict through Indigenous Women and Youth Project:
Â 
The ARC project leverages the role of women and youth to support safe and secure environments, while building the capacity of traditional leadership structures and supporting dialogue to mitigate fragmentation within indigenous groups. It recognizes women and youth as rights holders with a fundamental stake in sustaining peace, while calling for an end to impunity in Honduras.

The project follows a P2P approach, bringing together representatives of indigenous groups who experience systemic, structural and physical violence at the local, regional and national level. The project focuses on creating inclusive space for indigenous women and youth to participate meaningfully, but recognizes in order to achieve this, there must be a safe and secure environment. ARC is informed by rigorous gender and age-sensitive analysis, understanding patriarchal norms, traditional gender roles, as well as the gendered impacts of conflict and NRM challenges. The design of the project focuses on Gender Equality and Womenâ€™s Empowerment, while cognizant of sensitivities and risks to women and youth.

Protracted conflicts require a new, women-led approach to shift power to local populations so they can move from short-term humanitarian ways of working to integrated approaches involving localization, capacity building, humanitarian interventions, development and security, with the aim to leave no one behind. This action is designed to equip local civil society organisations (CSOs) and community-based front-line emergency actors and self-help groups (CBOs) with the resources to prepare and respond to crises. In Rakhine State, this action will enable local communities to design responsible, adaptable and accountable responses to crises â€“ community- and women-led responses as dynamic and incisive as the conflict-induced crises and natural disasters are destabilising and unpredictable. This unpredictabulity is compunded by the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic which will further affect the access to services and communities. This action has three components: 1) Local actorsâ€™ skills, capacities and knowledge are enhanced to lead responsibly managed, locally led first-line emergency responses; 2) Township contingency and response plans based on locally-led risk analysis established; and 3) Rapid emeregency response in Rakhine.Â
